Integrated Challenge

Place one integrated best-answer clinical judgment challenge after Objective 8 or 9.

Challenge title: “The Vital Signs Pattern Does Not Match Baseline”

Scenario: A fictional resident has a change in breathing pattern, altered skin color, and vital signs outside the expected range. The learner must decide the safest CNA action.

Design rule: Choices should all sound plausible, but only one should be the safest and most complete. Debrief must explain every option and the common trap behind it. This preserves the plan’s challenge/debrief rules while keeping answer-key logic protected.

Assessment Policy for Dry Run

Module 10 practice checks are learning activities. The scored Module 10 assessment is separate from instructional minutes.

Assessment sources may include:

terminology items;
route/contraindication decisions;
normal/abnormal range interpretation;
TPR sequencing;
BP equipment and procedure decisions;
pain scale/reporting scenarios;
charting-format questions.

Learner-facing remediation explains the concept but does not expose protected final answer keys. The current plan already requires module assessment time and final assessment time to be tracked separately from theory time.

Hands-On and Clinical Boundary

Online Module 10 may show procedures, demonstrate sequence, use checklists, and support learner preparation.

It must not say:

“competency validated online”;
“clinical hours earned online”;
“hands-on skill passed”;
“CDPH/TPRU approved” unless approval is actually granted.

The source-recommended clinical time is carried as a deferred in-person/evaluator-supported component, not an online certificate claim.

